sentence: With the highest-possible 99 Composite Rating, six stocks share top billing in the enterprise software industry group, including Salesforce.com ( CRM ), Paycom Software ( PAYC ) and ServiceNow ( NOW ).
LogMeIn ( LOGM ), which has just jumped into a new buy zone, also joins this elite list.

[ibd-display-video id=2102289 width=50 float=left autostart=true] Paycom and ServiceNow are extended beyond buy range from earlier breakouts, as are Ultimate Software ( ULTI ) and Ebix (EBIX), both of which also earn a 99 Composite Rating,

Salesforce.com, which provides customer relationship management ( CRM ) solutions, is trying to retake the 109.29 buy point it initially cleared on Jan. 9.
LogMeIn is a leader in remote-access software, pitting it against giant rivals Cisco Systems (CSCO) and Microsoft (MSFT).

Last year, LogMeIn completed a reverse merger with the GoToMeeting business of Citrix Systems (CTXS), and earlier this month, it agreed to buy Jive Communications in a deal that could ultimately cost $367 million.
The Boston-based company has delivered average EPS growth of 118% over the last three quarters, including a 107% spike in Q3.
Analysts are looking for an 88% rise when LogMeIn reports Q4 earnings after the close today.
Sales growth has also been impressive and accelerating, coming in between 135% and 216% over the last three quarters.
LogMeIn's 23% annual pretax profit margin and 26% return on equity are two more signs it's a very well-run company.
On Tuesday, LogMeIn jumped over 3% in volume more than double its daily average, closing the day 1% above a 128.45 entry.
Keep in mind that it is risky to buy any breakout stock just before an earnings report.
It's generally better to wait and see what kind of numbers the company reports and how the market reacts.
LogMeIn's rising relative strength line is near new high ground, a sign of market leadership.
The stock's Accumulation/Distribution Rating has now improved to a B+ and its up/down volume ratio has jumped to a solid 1.6, indicating rising institutional demand.
Early Thursday, LogMeIn was up over 2%, putting towards the upper end of the buy range, which extends to 134.87.
Salesforce was also up more than 2% and back above its prior buy point.
